              <h2><span style="font-weight: bold;">Running Perl on Windows</span></h2>
              <p><br />
              </p>
              <p><span style="font-weight: bold;">Installing Perl on Windows</span></p>
              <p>We are going to go over ActiveState Perl for Windows.  Their
                are other alternatives although ActiveState has become the
                leader for Microsoft Perl.  Note that I have found major issues
                with ActiveState 5.20.3 and SSL and recommend using 5.14 or 5.16. 
                Strawberry Perl is also a very popular alternative and may be
                worth looking into. </p>
              <p>installation is quite easy just download the installer for your
                version of windows and run.  It will install Perl along with a
                good generic set of libraries.  </p>
              <p>ActiveState lets you download most of the cpan libraries using
                their Perl Package Manager.  The Manager is quite easy to use
                and will download and install the libraries in the ActiveState
                distribution. </p>
              <p><span style="font-weight: bold;">Perl Programming on Windows</span></p>
              <p><span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: 'Lucida Grande', Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8000001907349px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">First
                  make sure you point to the correct binary in the first line of
                  your script "#!C:\perl64\bin\perl.exe -w" for example. 
                  ActiveState should have made .pl files executable during the
                  install.  The installer should add the .pl extension into
                  windows for you.  For IIS you also need to set up the needed
                  Perl extensions to point to the Perl executable (e.g. c:\perl\bin\perl.exe)
                  as IIS is independent of the set up windows extensions you
                  have set up.   <br />
                </span></p>
              <p><span style="color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: 'Lucida Grande', Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8000001907349px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; line-height: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; display: inline !important; float: none; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Their
                  are several noticeable differences if you are used to
                  programming in Linux or UNIX.  first is that the back ticks do
